Nov 10 2004	What a Nice Surprise	I was heading to London for a 2-week visit as a solo traveler, and was so dreading the usual grimey, depressing, and slightly-sinister hotel that London-On-A-Budget is famous for--and instead found my little sanctuary. Spotlessly clean (and I mean CLEAN--crisp, snowy sheets and towels, no dust-kittens in the corners, no cobwebs dangling from the ceiling, no cigarette stink, no sprinkling of pubic-hair on the bathroom floor, no mold or mildew anywhere); charmingly furnished (everything color-coordinated and in good condition); comfortable mattress; adequate lighting. I was stunned, to be honest. All this, plus good staff--Andrea and Nilda were the greatest: friendly, courteous, and responsive to anything I needed. Plus a super location: 3 minutes to Paddington and 5 minutes to Lancaster Gate, so this meant great train and tube transportation. I could also easily walk to so many places (Kensington museums, Trafalgar Square, Regent's Park and the London Zoo, to name a few); and lots of restaurants and shops, all within a 2 or 3 block radius. Plus a great price: because of the off-season (October) and the length of my stay, I got a double room, ensuite, for 40 GBP per night, a real bargain. My room was in the basement, which I surprisingly liked--it was cozy, warm, and welcoming after a wet and windy day of sightseeing (although it might be a bit stifling in summer, even with the window open). It was also pretty quiet, which, in a small, older hotel, is a relative term--the usual thumps, bumps, and occassional raised voice, but absolutely no traffic noise. The only downsides were minor: my room was fairly small (perfect for one person, a bit crowded for two), but that's normal for London. Breakfast was OK, nothing great (could've used yogurt and fresh fruit), but I never left hungry so it worked just fine for me. The stairs are somewhat steep and narrow, and could've been a problem if my suitcase had been any larger--not impossible, just awkward for a small woman like me to wrestle stuff around without taking a header off the landing. Oh, and one more good thing: the bathroom was great! All tile, well-lighted, good ventilation, lots of hot water. And don't forget immaculate. I was in heaven. No question about it--I'd stay here again in a heartbeat.	
